{[show S]One partner opens a minor and the opponent overcalls in a major, so responder must show values and the unbid suits without losing the major.
[BID 1D]You open the longer minor with an unbalanced hand and no five-card major, naming the suit at the one level. The opening starts the partnership's search for its best strain. Your partner has responding values and four cards in the unbid major, so makes a negative double. Over a one-level overcall the double promises four of any unbid major plus enough to compete, asking partner to describe rather than guessing a suit alone.
[BID 2N]You show a balanced hand with extra values and a stopper in the overcalled suit, inviting partner toward the best game. This natural notrump bid steers the partnership toward the most points-rich strain. Your partner names a genuine club suit, a five-card holding that gives the partnership a second place to play. The bid keeps the auction below game while the side hunts for its best fit.
[BID 3N]You place the final contract in notrump, judging the combined values and the stopper make nine tricks the surest game. With no eight-card major fit confirmed, notrump is the natural landing spot.
[show NS]North's 12 HCP with four spades and a five-card club suit answered South's strong 17-count, and with the heart overcall stopped twice the partnership settled in 3NT. The negative double showed the spades, but when no major fit jelled the side wisely chose notrump, which made. A well-judged auction that found the best-scoring game.}
